# SIDE QUEST — "The Catalogue of the Unwritten"  (requires sq.faolan_catalogue)
# Brother Faolan asked you to bring the Catalogue of the Unwritten — a book listing every work meant to be
# written and never was: the poems the plague took before they were penned, the confessions that died with
# the confessor. He's in it himself: a cycle of poems he shelved when he took vows. Grief for the uncreated.
class: FaolanSideQuestContent

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# "The Catalogue of the Unwritten" — what to do with the book of everything the world meant to make and didn't.
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
conversation: sq.unwritten.thread | The Catalogue of the Unwritten
node: 0 | Brother Faolan
  *(You bring the Catalogue of the Unwritten up out of the Sealed Stacks, and Brother Faolan's hands shake so badly he can barely take it. It is not a large book. It is the saddest object in the Realms: a complete index of every work that was meant to exist and never did — the masterworks the war interrupted, the genius the plague took at nineteen, the kindness someone meant to write down and forgot. He opens it, and his acquisitive fever is entirely gone, replaced by a man looking at a record of all the world's almosts.)* It's real. *(barely a whisper.)* I half-thought it was a — a scholar's legend, a thing we told ourselves *existed* to explain the *ache.* *(he turns a page, and flinches.)* But here it is. *Everything* never written. *(he looks up at you, and his eyes are wet.)* Twenty years I wanted this to make my *career.* And now I'm holding it and I find I can't — I can't *file* it, Returned. It's not an *accession.* It's a — it's a *graveyard* of *books that never got to be born.* What in the gods' names do I *do* with it?
  enter: SET sq.unwritten_thread_begun
  auto: 1
node: 1 | Brother Faolan
  *(He turns the pages with a reverence that is half terror, reading titles aloud despite himself.)* Listen. *(quietly.)* *"The Tide-Cantos, by a Baldur's Gate fishwife who could neither read nor write but composed them in her head across forty years and died before she found anyone to set them down."* *(he swallows.)* *"A Defense of the Doubting, by a Crown Wars scholar, burned with its author before the first line was inked."* *(his voice cracks.)* *"Letters to My Son, by a soldier who meant to write them every winter and was walled before the first."* *(he closes his eyes.)* They're all here. Every *almost.* Every *meant-to.* Every *masterwork* the world was *owed* and *never got* because the *maker* *died*, or *quit*, or *ran out of time*, or — *(he opens his eyes, and they're streaming)* — or *took vows*, and let the *poems* go *unwritten*, *year* on *year*, until they were just an *ache* where a *book* should be. *(he meets your eyes.)* I'm *in* here, Returned. A *page* of *me.* The *poems* about my *mother*, the *sea*, the things I was going to *say* before I became a man who *files* what *others* said. *(he holds the book to his chest.)* So *don't* tell me to *shelve* it. I've *shelved* things my whole *life* — *including myself.* *Tell* me what a *book* of *everything never written* is *for*, when *filing* it would just be *one more* unwritten thing locked in the dark.
  * [INSIGHT 18] "It's not a graveyard, Faolan — it's a *summons.* Every entry is a work that died of *not being made* — and half the makers in this book are *still alive.* The fishwife's gone, but you're not. The catalogue isn't a record of the dead's losses. It's a *to-do list for the living*, a goad: write the thing you keep meaning to, before you become an entry too." -> goad ?? deflect
  * "Read it aloud. Every unwritten title, spoken once, in the great hall — a funeral, at last, for everything the world meant to make and didn't. The books that died unborn died of *silence*, of never being heard. So give them a voice, even if it's only their titles. Let the never-written be *said*, once, by someone who understands what they cost." -> read_aloud
  * "Find your own page and write the poems off it. You shelved yourself twenty years ago, Faolan — but the poems about your mother and the sea aren't *gone*, they're *unwritten*, and unwritten isn't the same as impossible. You're not dead. You're just late. Read your page, and then make it a *lie*: write the books the catalogue swears you never will." -> faolan_writes | fx SET sq.faolan_writes_his_poems
  * "Think about what this means for the Wall. The Faithless didn't just lose their *lives* — they lost everything they'd have *made.* Every poem, every cup, every kindness still in them when they were walled. This catalogue is the Wall's *deepest* theft, the one no one counts: not just the souls, but all the works those souls were still carrying." -> walls_theft
node: goad | Brother Faolan
  *(He goes very still, and then his whole frame changes — the grief reshaping into something with a pulse.)* A *summons.* *(slowly.)* Not a graveyard. *(he flips through the pages with new, frantic eyes.)* *Half* the makers in this book — *(he scans)* — they're — *gods*, you're *right*, they're *not all dead* — *"A History of the Lower City, by a tavern-keeper, intended these thirty years, not yet begun"* — *she's* *alive*, I *know* her, she pours at the *Low Lantern* — *(he turns pages faster)* — *"A Treatise on Mercy, by a Doomguide who left the order, planned, unwritten"* — *"The Cartographer's Memoir, of the world before the fire, intended, never started"* — *(he looks up, electrified.)* These aren't *losses*, Returned. Not *yet.* They're — they're *appointments the makers keep* ***missing.*** *(fierce now.)* The *catalogue* doesn't *mourn* the *unwritten.* It *indicts* the *living* for *not-writing-yet.* *(he laughs, wet and amazed.)* What if I — what if Acquisitions stopped *acquiring* the *dead's* losses and started *hunting down* the *living* makers and *shoving* this *book* in their *faces* — *"you have an entry here. A masterwork you keep not-writing. The plague didn't take it. The war didn't burn it. You're just* late. *Now go and make it a* lie, *before time makes it* true."* *(he meets your eyes, transformed.)* *That's* what it's for. Not a *shelf.* A *goad.* The *one* book in *Candlekeep* whose *purpose* is to *empty itself* — to *send* the *living* off to *write* the *things* that would *otherwise* end up *here.* *(he grips the Catalogue.)* Help me *carry* it to the *makers* who *still* *have* *time.* Let's *un-write* the *Unwritten*, *one* *living* *procrastinator* at a *time.* *Starting* — *(he swallows)* — *starting* with the *worst* offender. The *monk* on the *page* about his *mother.* *Me.*
  enter: SET sq.unwritten_goad_the_living, SET sq.faolan_writes_his_poems, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.naeve +5
  auto: 2
node: read_aloud | Brother Faolan
  *(He clutches the book, and his eyes well, and slowly he nods — the acquisitive monk choosing, for once, voice over vault.)* Read it aloud. *(quietly.)* A *funeral.* (his voice fills.)* Yes. *Yes.* They died of *silence*, you understand — *that's* the *thing* about the *unwritten*, that's *how* they *died* the *first* time: *un-heard*, *un-spoken*, *un-made*, going *out* of the world *without a sound* because the *maker* *never* got to *give* them *one.* *(he opens the Catalogue.)* And to *shelve* them — to *lock* the *book* of the *never-said* in a *Sealed Stack* — would be to *kill* them a *second* time, the *same* way: in *silence.* *(he straightens, a vow forming.)* So I'll *read* them. *Every* *title.* *Aloud.* In the *great* *hall*, where the *First* *Readers* and the *whole* *library* must *hear* — *"The Tide-Cantos. A Defense of the Doubting. Letters to My Son."* — *every* *unwritten* *work*, *spoken*, *once*, so that the *books* that *never* got to *exist* get, at *last*, the *one* thing they were *denied*: to be *said*, *out loud*, by someone who *understands* what they *cost.* *(he meets your eyes, weeping.)* It won't *make* them. *Nothing* can *make* them now; the *makers* are *dust.* But a *thing* *spoken* is a *thing* that *briefly* *was* — and *ten thousand* *almosts*, *read* *aloud*, *once*, in a *hall* that *finally* *listens*, is a *funeral* the *uncreated* have *waited* *forever* for. *(he holds the book.)* Help me *read* the *Unwritten* their *own* *titles.* Let the *never-said* be *said.* It's the *only* *birth* they'll *ever* *get* — and the *only* *funeral.* *Both* at *once.* *Help* me *give* it to them.
  enter: SET sq.unwritten_read_aloud, SET act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +5
  auto: 2
node: faolan_writes | Brother Faolan
  *(He freezes, and his hand goes to a particular page — one he's clearly already found, already read, already wept over.)* My own page. *(barely a whisper.)* I've — *(he turns to it.)* I *found* it the *moment* you *handed* me the *book.* Of *course* I did. *Twenty* years of *wanting* this *volume* and the *first* thing I did was *look* *myself* *up.* *(he reads, voice breaking.)* *"A Cycle of Poems on the Sea and the Mother, by Faolan of Baldur's Gate, intended in his nineteenth year, abandoned at his vows, unwritten."* *(he closes his eyes.)* There it *is.* The *proof* I was, for *one* *young* *moment*, a *person* with *something* to *say* — *before* I became a *person* who *files* what *others* said. *(his voice fills, fierce through tears.)* And you're — you're saying it's a *lie.* Or it *could* be. *(he opens his eyes.)* *"Unwritten"* isn't *"impossible."* The *poems* aren't *gone* — they're *un-made*, and *I'm* not *dead*, I'm just — *(he laughs, wet)* — *late.* *Forty-one* and *late* and *still* *breathing* and *still*, *gods* *help* me, *able* to *hold* a *pen.* *(he grips the Catalogue.)* The *fishwife* *can't* write her *Cantos* — she's *dust.* But *Faolan* of *Baldur's* *Gate* can *still* *write* the *poems* about his *mother.* *(he meets your eyes, transformed.)* I'm going to *make* my *entry* a *lie.* I'm going to *write* the *cycle* I *shelved* at *nineteen* — *badly*, probably, *twenty* years *rusty* — and then I'm going to *cross* *myself* *out* of the *Catalogue* of the *Unwritten*, the *first* *crossing-out* in the *book's* *history*, and *prove* that an *entry* in the *book* of the *never-made* is *not* a *sentence* but a *dare.* *(he weeps and laughs at once.)* You came to *bring* me a *book* to *file.* You've *un-shelved* the *one* thing I *filed* the *deepest*: *myself.* *Help* me *write* the *poems*, Returned. Let me *read* the *page* that's *mine* — and then *un-write* it, *by* *writing* the *thing* it *swears* I *never* *will.*
  enter: SET sq.faolan_writes_his_poems, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.naeve +6
  auto: 2
node: walls_theft | Brother Faolan
  *(He stops, the scholar in him going pale as the implication unfolds across his face.)* The Wall's *deepest* theft. *(slowly.)* The works the *Faithless* would have *made.* *(he looks at the Catalogue with new horror.)* *Gods.* I never — we *count* the *Wall's* crime as the *souls.* The *lives.* The *people* *filed* to *nothing.* *(his voice tightens.)* But you're *right* — that's not the *whole* of it, it's not even the — *(he opens the Catalogue, scanning with dread.)* — *every* soul the *Wall* *took* was *still* *carrying* things *unmade.* *(he reads.)* *"A Defense of the Doubting, burned with its author"* — that *author* was *walled*, Returned, *Faithless*, *taken* *mid-thought* — *(he turns pages, faster, sicker.)* The *Wall* didn't *just* *steal* *Maerys* the *soldier.* It *stole* the *Letters to Her Company* she'd have *written* in *old* *age.* It didn't *just* *take* *Halen* the *potter* — it *took* every *cup* still in his *hands*, every *shape* he *hadn't* *thrown* *yet.* *(he meets your eyes, devastated.)* The *Catalogue* of the *Unwritten* is *half* *full* of *the* *Faithless* — not their *names*, their *works*, the *masterpieces* and *kindnesses* and *small* *true* *things* they were *still* *going* *to* *make* when the *harvest* *took* them. *(his voice breaks.)* That's the *theft* *no* *one* *counts.* The *Wall* *files* a *soul* to *"nothing"* — and *with* it, *every* *book*, *every* *cup*, *every* *song* that *soul* had *not* *yet* *made*, *unmade* *forever*, *added* to *this* — *(he grips the book)* — to *this* *graveyard* of *the* *would-have-been.* *(he looks at you, fierce now.)* *Carry* this to the *Court.* Let the *powers* who *count* the *Faithless* as *"nothing"* *read* the *Catalogue* and *see* the *true* *size* of *what* they *stole*: not *just* *eleven* *thousand* *souls*, but *eleven* *thousand* *libraries* *of* *the* *unmade*, *every* *work* those *souls* were *still* *carrying*, *filed* to *nothing* *with* them. *The Wall didn't only kill the makers. It killed everything they hadn't made yet.* *That's* the *deepest* *theft.* *Let* the *Catalogue* *prove* it.
