node: 2 | Brother Faolan
  *(Brother Faolan holds the Catalogue of the Unwritten — the saddest object in the Realms, the complete index of everything the world meant to make and didn't, half of it the unmade works of the Faithless the Wall took mid-creation — and looks at you, the acquisitive monk who came to file a graveyard and found a summons instead.)*
  * "All of it: read the dead's entries aloud as the funeral they were owed, goad the living ones to write before time makes their entries true, and carry the whole catalogue to the Court as proof of the Wall's deepest theft. A funeral for the lost, a dare to the living, and an indictment of the machine that filled half its pages." -> all | fx SET sq.unwritten_read_aloud, SET sq.unwritten_goad_the_living, SET sq.unwritten_the_walls_theft, appr.garrow +4
  * "Start a second book beside it: the Catalogue of the *Written-After-All.* Every time a living maker crosses themselves out — writes the thing they meant to — record it in the new book. Let Candlekeep keep, for once, not a graveyard of almosts but a ledger of *deadlines beaten*, growing page by page as the Unwritten empties." -> second_book | fx SET sq.unwritten_written_after_all, SET act5.unbroken_line, appr.naeve +4
  * "You shelved yourself for twenty years, Faolan, and so did half these scholars — each keeping a locked library inside their own abandoned youth. Don't just work the Catalogue. *Heal the cataloguers.* Find the monks and readers who quit being makers to become filers, and hand each of them their own page. Un-shelve the whole library, the people first." -> heal_the_filers | fx SET sq.unwritten_heal_the_filers, appr.ilfaeril +4
node: all | Brother Faolan
  *(He gathers the Catalogue to his chest with the resolve of a man who has finally found the use for the book — and the use for himself.)* All of it. *(fierce, weeping, alight.)* A *funeral*, a *dare*, and an *indictment.* *(he ticks it off.)* For the *dead* makers — the *fishwife*, the *burned* *scholar*, the *soldier* *walled* *mid-letter* — I'll *read* their *entries* *aloud*, in the *great* *hall*, the *funeral* the *uncreated* *waited* *forever* for. *(he turns pages.)* For the *living* ones — the *tavern-keeper*, the *cartographer*, the *monk* on the *mother-and-sea* *page* — I'll *hunt* them *down* and *shove* the *book* in their *faces*: *"write* it, *you're* *late*, *not* *dead* — *make* your *entry* a *lie* *before* *time* *makes* it *true."* *(his voice rings.)* And for the *Wall* — *(he grips the book)* — I'll *carry* the *Catalogue* to the *Court*, and *prove* the *theft* *no* *one* *counts*: that the *machine* *filed* *eleven* *thousand* *libraries* of the *unmade* to *"nothing,"* every *work* the *Faithless* were *still* *carrying* when it *took* them. *(he meets your eyes, transformed from filer to maker.)* *Twenty* *years* I *acquired* and *shelved* and *locked* *away*, and *called* it *preservation*, and the *whole* *time* I was *building* a *tomb* — for the *books*, for the *grief*, for *myself.* *(he laughs, wet and free.)* And you've *handed* me the *one* *accession* that *taught* me the *difference* between a *library* and a *graveyard*: a *library* *sends* you *out* to *make* *more.* *(he opens the Catalogue.)* *Funeral*, *dare*, *indictment.* The *dead* *spoken*, the *living* *goaded*, the *Wall* *named.* And *me* — *(he finds his page)* — *me*, *first*, *crossed* *out*, by *writing* the *poems* I *shelved* at *nineteen.* *Let's* *empty* the *Unwritten*, Returned. *Every* *way* at *once.*
